 abovementioned arcane group of musicians; much of Lawes's surviving consort music appears to have been written to be performed by this group. The remainder of the book deals with William Lawes the composer. The second section is a detailed study of Lawes's autograph sources: the first of its kind. It includes 62 black and white facsimile images, and complete inventories of all the autographs, and presents ground-breaking new research into Lawes's scribal hand, the sources and their functions, and new evidence for their chronology. The third section comprises six chapters on Lawes's consort music; in these chapters various topics are examined, such as chronology, Lawes's compositional process, and the relationship between Lawes's music and the court context from which it arose. This book willbe of interest to scholars working on English music in the Early Modern period, but also to those interested in source studies, compositional process and the function of music in the Early Modern court. JOHN CUNNINGHAMis a Senior Lecturer in Music, at Bangor University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChamber musicxHistory and criticismy17th centuryzEngland. 0aChamber musiczEnglandxHistory and criticismy17th century. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCharles I.  aEarly Modern court.  aEarly Modern period.  aEnglish composer.  aEnglish music.  aJOHN CUNNINGHAM.  aLutes, Viols and Voices.  aSiege of Chester.  aWilliam Lawes.  acivil war.  acompositional process.  aseventeenth century.  asource studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846158254?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158254423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9